SUMMARIZER="A">  

The Maine constitution used to guarantee the right to keep and bear
arms "for the common defense." In 1986 the Maine Supreme Court upheld
a gun violation by focusing on the "common defense" phrase. The
legislature, in response, enacted a constitutional amendment deleting
that language declaring "Every citizen has a right to keep and bear
arms, and this right shall never be questioned." The amendment was
approved by voters in November 1987. Now a county superior court
justice has ruled that even a convicted felon may own guns based on
the amendment's all-inclusive language. The Maine Attorney General has
announced that he will appeal the decision.</SUM>

<SUM
